# PowerShell-safe command chaining (Windows)

When running shell commands in this repo on **Windows PowerShell**, **do not use `&&`** to chain commands. In many PowerShell setups it is **not a valid operator**, which causes avoidable failures during workflows like `/review`, `/commit`, etc.

## Rules

- **Never** emit `cmd1 && cmd2` in PowerShell.
- Prefer **separate commands** (two distinct invocations) when possible.
- If a single line is required, use `;` plus an explicit “stop on failure” check:

```powershell
cmd1; if ($LASTEXITCODE -ne 0) { exit $LASTEXITCODE }; cmd2
```

## Examples

Bad (breaks in PowerShell):

```powershell
git status && git diff
```

Good (PowerShell-safe):

```powershell
git status
git diff
```

Good single-line (PowerShell-safe, stops on failure):

```powershell
git status; if ($LASTEXITCODE -ne 0) { exit $LASTEXITCODE }; git diff
```

